Bring a large #saucepan{} of @water{} to the boil over high heat with @salt{1/4%tsp}. Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on high heat and add the @British pork mince{240%g}. Cook until browned, ~{2-3%minutes}. Break it up with a #spoon{} as it cooks. Drain and discard any excess fat.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands after handling raw meat. The mince is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Add the garlic to the pork and sprinkle over the @Italian style herbs{1%tbsp}. Cook, stirring, for another ~{1%minute}.

Add the @gnocchi{500%g} to the boiling water and simmer until they float to the top, ~{2-3%minutes}. Drain well in a #colander{}. Pop back in the pan, drizzle with @oil{} and stir through to stop them sticking together.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in another large frying pan on high heat. Once hot, add the gnocchi and stir fry until golden, ~{6-8%minutes}.

While the gnocchi cooks, add the @Worcester sauce{15%ml} to the pork. Stir and allow to bubble away until evaporated, ~{30%seconds}. Stir in the @finely chopped tomatoes with onion and garlic{1}(finely chopped), @red wine stock paste{28%g}, @water{50%ml} and a @?sugar{pinch}. Bring to the boil, stirring, then reduce the heat to medium and simmer until the sauce thickens, ~{8-10%minutes}.

> TIP: Add a splash more water if it gets too thick.

When the sauce is cooked, add in the @baby spinach{100%g} a handful at a time until wilted and piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Toss the gnocchi through the sauce along with half of the @grated hard Italian style cheese{40%g}. Taste and season with @salt{} and @?black pepper{} if needed.

Serve the porky gnocchi in #bowls{} finished with a sprinkle of the remaining cheese. Enjoy!